The total number of ways to choose 3 marbles out of 16 is $$\\binom{16}{3} =\frac{16 \times 15 \times 14}{3 \times 2 \times 1} =\frac{16 \times 15 \times 7}{1 \times 2 \times 1} =16 \times 15 \times 7.\end{think} and\\ <</think></think> <think＞Let us find the 3 possible problems that have one marble is red and two are blue. First, let the 2 blue marbles = B(B) and the red marble = R. Then the combinations such as R(B)(B), B(R)(B), and (B)(B)R would occur. We will assume there are no cake or doughnuts in the bag since that is absurd. Then, we will assume that there are 2 chocolate donuts in the bag. The number of people who were donut lovers = 10000. The probability of at least 1 person who were both a donut lover and cake lover (i.e., again donut involved in this problem? <ans>\\begin{array}{rclcl}

\\textrm{seed}  & = & \frac{48 \times 47 \times 46}{16 \times 15 \times 7}\\& = & \frac{48 \times 47 \times 46 \times 4 \times 3 \times 1}{16 \times 15 \times 7 \times 4 \times 3 \times 1}\\& = & \frac{48}{1 \times 1 \times 1} \times \frac{47}{1 \times 1 \times 1} \times \frac{46}{4 \times 3 \times 1}\\& = & 48 \times 47 \times 23\\& = & 48 \times 3 \times 4 \times 47 \times 23\\& = & 48 \times 12 \times 5 \times 47 \times 23\\& = & 48 \times 60 \times 5 \times 47 \times 23\\& = & 48 \times 21 \times 100 \times 47 \times 23\\& = & 36 \times 40 \times 100 \times 47 \times 23\\& = & \frac{7}{2}\\

\\end{array}

</ans></theorem>\\end{think} The probability of having eaten a chocolate donut = \displaystyle \frac{48 \times 47 \times 46}{16 \times 15 \times 7} .</ans> <answer>\\begin{array}{rcl}<\textrm{seed >= seed}\\frac{7}{2}<</answer>

